articles.headline: VW Is Said to Cheat on Diesel Emissions; U.S. to Order Big Recall
articles.snippet: The Environmental Protection Agency issued a notice of violation, accusing VW of installing software known as a “defeat device” in 4-cylinder vehicles.
articles.abstract: The Environmental Protection Agency issued a notice of violation, accusing VW of installing software known as a “defeat device” in 4-cylinder vehicles.
articles.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Obama administration on Friday directed Volkswagen to recall nearly a half-million cars, saying the automaker illegally installed software in its diesel-power cars to evade standards for reducing smog.
articles.byline: By Coral Davenport and Jack Ewing

articles.headline: Family Pond Boils at Center of a ‘Regulatory War’ in Wyoming
articles.snippet: Andy Johnson’s watering hole has become an emblem for conservatives and local governments fighting the reach of the federal government.
articles.abstract: Andy Johnson’s watering hole has become an emblem for conservatives and local governments fighting the reach of the federal government.
articles.lead_paragraph: FORT BRIDGER, Wyo. — The sun was sinking and the brook trout were biting, so Andy Johnson and his daughter Aspen, 6, stepped onto their sun-bleached pier, hooked some mealworms and cast their lines into the most infamous pond in the West.
articles.byline: By Jack Healy

articles.headline: Watching the Fed, and Remembering the Tequila Crisis
articles.snippet: Twenty years ago, a series of rate increases by the Federal Reserve put pressure on emerging markets like Mexico, which had to be bailed out by the United States and the I.M.F. Could it happen again?
articles.abstract: Twenty years ago, a series of rate increases by the Federal Reserve put pressure on emerging markets like Mexico, which had to be bailed out by the United States and the I.M.F. Could it happen again?
articles.lead_paragraph: Lots of buzz concerning the impact of higher interest rates in the United States. A major trading partner creating shock waves in the global economy. Stock market volatility spreading around the world.
articles.byline: By Nelson D. Schwartz

articles.headline: Bowe Bergdahl Should Not Be Imprisoned, Army Investigator Says
articles.snippet: The investigator, Maj. Gen. Kenneth R. Dahl, testified at a hearing that will help determine whether the sergeant will be court-martialed for disappearing in Afghanistan in 2009.
articles.abstract: The investigator, Maj. Gen. Kenneth R. Dahl, testified at a hearing that will help determine whether the sergeant will be court-martialed for disappearing in Afghanistan in 2009.
articles.lead_paragraph: SAN ANTONIO — The general who led the Army’s investigation into the disappearance of Sgt. Bowe Bergdahl from his remote outpost in Afghanistan in 2009 said on Friday that sentencing the sergeant to prison would be “inappropriate.”
articles.byline: By Richard A. Oppel Jr

articles.headline: U.A.W. Contract With Fiat Chrysler Would Give 2nd-Tier Workers Big Raise
articles.snippet: The proposed contract would substantially narrow the pay gap between entry-level workers, who now earn as little as $16 an hour, and veteran workers, who get $28.
articles.abstract: The proposed contract would substantially narrow the pay gap between entry-level workers, who now earn as little as $16 an hour, and veteran workers, who get $28.
articles.lead_paragraph: DETROIT — The proposed contract between Fiat Chrysler Automobiles and the United Automobile Workers union includes wage increases that significantly close the gap in pay between veteran workers and entry-level employees.
articles.byline: By Bill Vlasic and Mary M. Chapman

articles.headline: A Humble Pope, Challenging the World
articles.snippet: Francis, the first Latin American pope, has drawn from his life in Argentina to try to create a humbler papacy, albeit one with lofty ambitions. His push for change has stirred hope and anxiety.
articles.abstract: Francis, the first Latin American pope, has drawn from his life in Argentina to try to create a humbler papacy, albeit one with lofty ambitions. His push for change has stirred hope and anxiety.
articles.lead_paragraph: VATICAN CITY — Days after the election of Pope Francis, word reached the Vatican press office that the new pontiff was unexpectedly celebrating morning Mass. Other popes had presided over morning services, too, but as the world (and the Vatican press office) would soon realize, Francis did things his own way.
articles.byline: By Jim Yardley

articles.headline: Enabling of Ad Blocking in Apple’s iOS 9 Prompts Backlash
articles.snippet: Apps that block all ads are threatening some web publishers’ livelihoods, which in turn could threaten some content on the web.
articles.abstract: Apps that block all ads are threatening some web publishers’ livelihoods, which in turn could threaten some content on the web.
articles.lead_paragraph: For years, people have longed for ways to stop advertising from popping up on their iPhones and iPads. Now, software to block ads on these gadgets has arrived — and the harsh realities of the practice are causing second thoughts.
articles.byline: By Katie Benner and Sydney Ember

articles.headline: In Unit Stalked by Suicide, Veterans Try to Save One Another
articles.snippet: Members of a Marine battalion that served in a restive region in Afghanistan have been devastated by the deaths of comrades and frustrated by the V.A.
articles.abstract: Members of a Marine battalion that served in a restive region in Afghanistan have been devastated by the deaths of comrades and frustrated by the V.A.
articles.lead_paragraph: After the sixth suicide in his old battalion, Manny Bojorquez sank onto his bed. With a half-empty bottle of Jim Beam beside him and a pistol in his hand, he began to cry.
articles.byline: By Dave Philipps

articles.headline: In Philadelphia, Putting on a Show for a Holy Headliner
articles.snippet: Production companies helping orchestrate the planning of Pope Francis’s visit have to balance the needs of bishops, pop stars, politicians and a million pilgrims.
articles.abstract: Production companies helping orchestrate the planning of Pope Francis’s visit have to balance the needs of bishops, pop stars, politicians and a million pilgrims.
articles.lead_paragraph: More than a month before Pope Francis was scheduled to arrive in Philadelphia for two days of speeches, celebrations and communion, Scott Mirkin, a local concert producer, was staring at a grassy patch in front of the Philadelphia Museum of Art, trying to ensure that the papal visit also would be a decent piece of entertainment.
articles.byline: By David Gelles

articles.headline: U.S. and China Seek Arms Deal for Cyberspace
articles.snippet: The countries are discussing what could be the first arms control accord for cyberspace, and an agreement could be announced as soon as Thursday, according to officials.
articles.abstract: The countries are discussing what could be the first arms control accord for cyberspace, and an agreement could be announced as soon as Thursday, according to officials.
articles.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The United States and China are negotiating what could become the first arms control accord for cyberspace, embracing a commitment by each country that it will not be the first to use cyberweapons to cripple the other’s critical infrastructure during peacetime, according to officials involved in the talks.
articles.byline: By David E. Sanger

articles.headline: Party Rules to Streamline Race May Backfire for G.O.P.
articles.snippet: The rule changes, which were intended to hasten the nominating process, have failed to narrow a sprawling field while potentially aiding Donald J. Trump’s chances.
articles.abstract: The rule changes, which were intended to hasten the nominating process, have failed to narrow a sprawling field while potentially aiding Donald J. Trump’s chances.
articles.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — When gloomy Republican Party leaders regrouped after President Obama’s 2012 re-election, they were intent on enhancing the party’s chances of winning back the White House. The result: new rules to head off a prolonged and divisive nomination fight, and to make certain the Republican standard-bearer is not pulled too far to the right before Election Day.
articles.byline: By Adam Nagourney and Jonathan Martin

articles.headline: Pope Francis, Arriving in Cuba, Seeks to Revive Church
articles.snippet: Francis arrived in Havana on Saturday for the first stop of a nine-day papal trip that includes the United States. The first Latin American pope must now try to open up Cuba to the Roman Catholic Church.
articles.abstract: Francis arrived in Havana on Saturday for the first stop of a nine-day papal trip that includes the United States. The first Latin American pope must now try to open up Cuba to the Roman Catholic Church.
articles.lead_paragraph: HAVANA — In brokering the historic thaw between Cuba and the United States, Pope Francis stepped squarely into the thorny realm of geopolitics, sending letters to the presidents of both nations, playing host to secret meetings in the halls of the Vatican and nudging the Cold War enemies to put a half-century of vitriol and mistrust behind them.
articles.byline: By Jim Yardley, Azam Ahmed and Victoria Burnett

articles.headline: Horror Drove Her From South. 100 Years Later, She Returned.
articles.snippet: After decades of saying she didn’t even want to see the state on a map, Mamie Lang Kirkland returned to Ellisville, Miss., 100 years after her family fled a lynch mob.
articles.abstract: After decades of saying she didn’t even want to see the state on a map, Mamie Lang Kirkland returned to Ellisville, Miss., 100 years after her family fled a lynch mob.
articles.lead_paragraph: ELLISVILLE, Miss. — The dark S.U.V. rented for the occasion stopped outside the one-story City Hall. A wheelchair was rolled up to receive a petite passenger wearing a baseball cap dappled with sparkles, her hair gray-white, her skin mocha brown, her socks hot pink.
articles.byline: By Dan Barry

articles.headline: As Profile Rises, Carly Fiorina Aims to Redefine Record as a C.E.O.
articles.snippet: The presidential hopeful has prepared to counter accusations that she mismanaged Hewlett-Packard and callously laid off workers — the kind of criticism that hurt her in a 2010 Senate race.
articles.abstract: The presidential hopeful has prepared to counter accusations that she mismanaged Hewlett-Packard and callously laid off workers — the kind of criticism that hurt her in a 2010 Senate race.
articles.lead_paragraph: Carly Fiorina was ready when CNN’s Jake Tapper asked her to respond to criticism about her record at Hewlett-Packard during last week’s Republican debate.
articles.byline: By Amy Chozick and Quentin Hardy

articles.headline: Pope Francis Careful in Navigating Cuban Politics
articles.snippet: Pope Francis is enormously influential in his native region, raising expectations that he will wade into regional politics while in Cuba.
articles.abstract: Pope Francis is enormously influential in his native region, raising expectations that he will wade into regional politics while in Cuba.
articles.lead_paragraph: HAVANA — Revolution Square is the political stage of revolutionary Cuba. Fidel Castro held huge rallies here to castigate the imperialists up north. Looming over the square are immense portraits of the revolutionaries Che Guevara and Camilo Cienfuegos.
articles.byline: By Jim Yardley and Azam Ahmed

articles.headline: U.S. Will Accept More Refugees as Crisis Grows
articles.snippet: Under the plan, the limit on visas for refugees would be increased to 100,000 by 2017, a significant increase over the current annual cap of 70,000.
articles.abstract: Under the plan, the limit on visas for refugees would be increased to 100,000 by 2017, a significant increase over the current annual cap of 70,000.
articles.lead_paragraph: BERLIN — The Obama administration will increase the number of worldwide refugees the United States accepts each year to 100,000 by 2017, a significant increase over the current annual cap of 70,000, Secretary of State John Kerry said Sunday.
articles.byline: By Michael R. Gordon, Alison Smale and Rick Lyman

articles.headline: Drug Goes From $13.50 a Tablet to $750, Overnight
articles.snippet: The price of the drug, called Daraprim, a standard of care for treating a life-threatening parasitic infection, went to $750 a tablet from $13.50.
articles.abstract: The price of the drug, called Daraprim, a standard of care for treating a life-threatening parasitic infection, went to $750 a tablet from $13.50.
articles.lead_paragraph: Specialists in infectious disease are protesting a gigantic overnight increase in the price of a 62-year-old drug that is the standard of care for treating a life-threatening parasitic infection.
articles.byline: By Andrew Pollack

articles.headline: U.S. Soldiers Told to Ignore Sexual Abuse of Boys by Afghan Allies
articles.snippet: The American military’s policy has been to look the other way on “boy play” by Afghan commanders. One Marine’s father believes it was a factor in his son’s death.
articles.abstract: The American military’s policy has been to look the other way on “boy play” by Afghan commanders. One Marine’s father believes it was a factor in his son’s death.
articles.lead_paragraph: KABUL, Afghanistan — In his last phone call home, Lance Cpl. Gregory Buckley Jr. told his father what was troubling him: From his bunk in southern Afghanistan, he could hear Afghan police officers sexually abusing boys they had brought to the base.
articles.byline: By Joseph Goldstein

articles.headline: Volkswagen to Stop Sales of Diesel Cars Involved in Recall
articles.snippet: The automaker is facing regulatory action in the United States over accusations that it installed software to evade smog-fighting standards.
articles.abstract: The automaker is facing regulatory action in the United States over accusations that it installed software to evade smog-fighting standards.
articles.lead_paragraph: FRANKFURT — Volkswagen said on Sunday that it would halt sales of cars in the United States equipped with the kind of diesel motors that had led regulators to accuse the German company of illegally installing software to evade standards for reducing smog.
articles.byline: By Jack Ewing and Coral Davenport

articles.headline: Software Is Smart Enough for SAT, but Still Far From Intelligent
articles.snippet: In a first, an artificial intelligence program answered math questions on the SAT by understanding diagrams and sentences, but scientists say machine thinking is still a long way off.
articles.abstract: In a first, an artificial intelligence program answered math questions on the SAT by understanding diagrams and sentences, but scientists say machine thinking is still a long way off.
articles.lead_paragraph: SEATTLE — An artificial intelligence software program capable of seeing and reading has for the first time answered geometry questions from the SAT at the level of an average 11th grader.
articles.byline: By John Markoff

articles.headline: Kickstarter Focuses Its Mission on Altruism Over Profit
articles.snippet: Yancey Strickler and Perry Chen, the crowdfunding site’s co-founders, announce that their company is reincorporating as a “public benefit corporation.”
articles.abstract: Yancey Strickler and Perry Chen, the crowdfunding site’s co-founders, announce that their company is reincorporating as a “public benefit corporation.”
articles.lead_paragraph: Many technology start-ups aim to become “unicorns,” the companies that get valued at $1 billion or more on their way to probable vast riches. Yancey Strickler and Perry Chen have no interest in that.
articles.byline: By Mike Isaac and David Gelles

articles.headline: On Instagram and Other Social Media, Redefining ‘User Engagement’
articles.snippet: The intersection between brands trying to capitalize on social media activity and people’s expectation of privacy has become murky.
articles.abstract: The intersection between brands trying to capitalize on social media activity and people’s expectation of privacy has become murky.
articles.lead_paragraph: Shereen Way did not think twice about posting a photo on Instagram of her 4-year-old daughter wearing a green dress and pink Crocs sandals.
articles.byline: By Sydney Ember and Rachel Abrams

articles.headline: A Firing at The Los Angeles Times Focuses Discontent
articles.snippet: Austin Beutner’s departure as publisher, a position he had held only a year, widened a divide between The Los Angeles Times and its corporate parent in Chicago.
articles.abstract: Austin Beutner’s departure as publisher, a position he had held only a year, widened a divide between The Los Angeles Times and its corporate parent in Chicago.
articles.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — In January, Jack Griffin, the chief executive of Tribune Publishing Company, took his senior management team to visit The Los Angeles Times, the jewel in his company’s portfolio of newspapers.
articles.byline: By Ravi Somaiya

articles.headline: Xi Jinping of China Arriving in U.S. at Moment of Vulnerability
articles.snippet: The chill on the Chinese economy has eroded some of the sheen attached to Mr. Xi, and some analysts say he may want to project an especially strong image when holding talks in the United States.
articles.abstract: The chill on the Chinese economy has eroded some of the sheen attached to Mr. Xi, and some analysts say he may want to project an especially strong image when holding talks in the United States.
articles.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — President Xi Jinping of China looked regal as he stood in a limousine moving past Tiananmen Square this month, wearing a traditional suit of the kind favored by Mao and waving at parade troops assembled at attention. But the luster of Mr. Xi’s imperial presidency has dulled lately.
articles.byline: By Chris Buckley and Jane Perlez

articles.headline: Trading Meat for Tires as Bartering Economy Grows in Greece
articles.snippet: As Greece grapples with a continued downturn, bartering is gaining traction at the margins of the economy, a worrisome sign for Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras who was re-elected on Sunday.
articles.abstract: As Greece grapples with a continued downturn, bartering is gaining traction at the margins of the economy, a worrisome sign for Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras who was re-elected on Sunday.
articles.lead_paragraph: ATHENS — Thodoris Roussos stood in his butcher’s shop and pointed to a large white delivery truck at the curb. For months, he had put off replacing the tires, because Greece’s financial crisis had cut into business. But recently, he upgraded the van with a set of good wheels at a price that could not be beat.
articles.byline: By Liz Alderman

articles.headline: Devoted to Simplicity, Pope Francis Creates Knotty Logistics With Visit
articles.snippet: Nothing is simple about a six-day, three-city papal trip that is a cross between a military operation, a diplomatic mission and an arena-rock tour.
articles.abstract: Nothing is simple about a six-day, three-city papal trip that is a cross between a military operation, a diplomatic mission and an arena-rock tour.
articles.lead_paragraph: In New York, Roman Catholic officials have walked Pope Francis’ expected path through the National September 11 Memorial and timed it at five to seven minutes.
articles.byline: By Andy Newman and Vivian Yee
